Nailing your entries requires a combination of perfecting your risk/reward setups and mastering your multiple timeframe analysis. Both of them are vital to me in order to reach consistent profitability.

https://t.co/cLrdkgS3i7

https://t.co/duzgqU8TnB

I highly improved my risk/reward trading back in 2014-2016 on the OkCoin Futures. As a novice trader I always leveraged my positions on 10x or 20x, so finding great entries was crucial to avoid the infamous margin calls. After around 2 years and 400.000 transactions, I was finally getting better at finding the ‚Äòpoints of no return‚Äô (PNRs) in the chart. Those points often reveal themselves by leaving small clues in the lower timeframes. But without a full and complete analysis of all the timeframes, you will not be able to spot and/or anticipate them. Clues are only clues when found in the right place and at the right time. Next to this, your risk/reward setups need to be outstanding if you want your overall performance to survive multiple failed entries.

Before looking for PNRs, you need to determine the points of acceleration (PAs) in the chart for both bulls and bears. At these price points, the candles will accelerate as they will hit liquidity and/or change sentiment. Your furthest PA is often your target or your breakout zone, and your closest PA is often, but not always, the first step towards that zone. The closer they are the better, and more PAs mean more gusts in your sail, especially needed if you‚Äôre going upwind.

After you have established your roadmap (how do you need the chart to move before and after your entry) for both the bullish and the bearish case, the beautiful battle begins: which candles should print in what way in order to reach which PA in what required time. Only when you are completely zoned in on synchronizing your timeframes (from 1minute until 1month), you will be able to read that battle. It shouldn‚Äôt matter if you are bullish or bearish because the chart will show you who‚Äôs winning which timeframes. It is at this time that your bias (that includes fundamental analysis) is either confirmed or proven wrong. Don‚Äôt act on the first weaknesses or strengths, the battle takes and gives, but determine the lines in the sand and the inflection points, that‚Äôs where every bullet counts.

Now that you‚Äôve got your entry for a short-term swing and the roadmap that it should follow, will it manifest in the medium and/or long term? Keep analysing all the upcoming candles, plan all the different ways that they should or could close to either confirm or disprove your trade. Ask yourself continuously why certain candles closed in what kind of way, and how they could fit into your time-based roadmap. Keep rewriting the outcomes when candles close atypical, because every candle should close in a way that fits into your narrative. And if it doesn‚Äôt, find out if you missed something, because it doesn‚Äôt necessarily mean that you‚Äôre in the wrong trade. After your entry you need to monitor and investigate every step and melt the candles and their respective timeframes into one movement.

Unfortunately becoming consistently profitable in trading requires a lot more than just the above two aspects. It‚Äôs one of those professions where you have to master all elements in order to make money consistently. A steep learning curve and perseverance will get you through the first part. The middle part is a combination of technicals and behavioural finance. The last part is all about passion.

To start, a summary of what DePIN is:

Decentralized Physical Infrastructure Networks

Where blockchain and tokens are used for infrastructure in the physical world.

---- 

As mentioned, DePIN mindshare currently sits at only 2.5%, roughly 10x smaller than AI, for example.

But, this 2.5% is a result of explosive growth in the past year.

Last September, it was around 0.5% and has been up only since then.

Some of the projects driving it forward:
- @Hivemapper 
- @helium 
- @AethirCloud 
- @ionet 
- @rendernetwork 

----

Helium has been one of the standout performers.

From a token perspective, $HNT has 4x'd since last year and continues to show strength recently.

But off-chain it has also had success, with mindshare and sentiment also on the way up.

Importantly, its impact on the physical world has also been growing, with over 100,000 users of the Helium phone network and partnerships with top US providers.

Some of the people who had been shouting its praises:
- @AustinBarack 
- @Shaughnessy119
- @_tolks

----

Back to DePIN more generally:

Using our AI to pull across all the top sources in crypto, we can summarise the bullish theses people have written.

Solana stands out as the chain of choice, and the areas of most interest tend to revolve around data, energy and mapping.

Now, as you always should, let's also see what people are most bearish about generally.

----

Overall, DePIN appears to be in the early stage of growth, though as we know, in crypto narratives can disappear fast.

The optimistic part about DePIN is it has that real world impact to potentially carry it through.

Learn to explain the ‚Äúwhy‚Äù element of any strategy/heuristic you use. Most strategies are highly situational. If you cannot understand why something happens, then you‚Äôre just throwing darts with a blindfold

Let‚Äôs take for instance ‚Äúprice reverts to the mean more often during Asia sessions‚Äù

Does this mean you long every dip during Asia? No

Let‚Äôs dive into the ‚Äúwhy‚Äù for why price mean reverts during Asia. It‚Äôs likely because books are thinner and the market can see when a move is driven by high slippage/shitty execution. Mean reversion algos also become more impactful during illiquid sessions

Now that we know this heuristic is mostly technical, we know not to apply it in the presence of any clear fundamental drivers

Let‚Äôs assume you get a significant dip because of a critical BOJ announcement. Let‚Äôs also assume there weren‚Äôt many liquidations/high slippage orders. Should you rush to long? Probably not

‚ÄúPrice often revisits poor highs/lows‚Äù -> mkt didn‚Äôt get to transact for a long period perhaps due to illiquidity, and many prospective orders weren‚Äôt filled 

‚ÄúBuy the EMA crossover!‚Äù -> brainless algos and traders look at this indicator and fire off

‚ÄúLevels can determine supports/resistances‚Äù -> trapped traders can dominate the flow in the absence of any catalyst 

Etc

Explain it. Consequently, know when this works and when it doesn‚Äôt. Find ways to quantify and strengthen your evidence as well

Small alpha leak: the CME closes for an hour from 5-6pm ET. The market becomes extra thin during this window, resulting in exaggerated moves. Price *usually* mean reverts after 6pm, but of course this all depends on general positioning and the magnitude of the move

It‚Äôs v similar to the weekend

Take a look at the BTC CME chart from today. Closed 62k at 5pm, opened 60.5k at 6pm further pushing price down to 58k for the next 15mins as momentum/trend algos trading on the CME were triggered

Counter trading that second leg down particularly gives a p decent mean reversion opportunity if you‚Äôre a high frequency trader

As with any indicator, understand how liquidation heatmaps are calculated and what kind of limitations that can create. 
They‚Äôre mostly approximations drawn from increases in OI along with volume in a certain direction

They‚Äôre static and don‚Äôt update as ppl close/manage positions. They also assume a certain distribution for leverage (eg if OI increased by $50m, then the heatmap distributes it like 25% 100x, 25% 50x, etc. which is def not the case). They don‚Äôt factor in added collateral. And so on

Nonetheless, they can sometimes be useful for short term trades/scalps where one can assume the positioning isn‚Äôt super dynamic

I‚Äôve talked abt this trade maybe a million times on here. It‚Äôs not manipulation, it‚Äôs just how markets structurally work. Funds don‚Äôt day trade their books (you rly don‚Äôt wanna see that tax bill), they *hedge*. Particularly with CPI where many risk assets have gotten clobbered in the past, participants tend to be overly cautious, regardless of the anticipated print/outcome. ‚ÄúKoalas are fucking horrible animals.

They have one of the smallest brain to body ratios of any mammal, additionally - their brains are smooth. A brain is folded to increase the surface area for neurons. If you present a koala with leaves plucked from a branch, laid on a flat surface, the koala will not recognise it as food. They are too thick to adapt their feeding behaviour to cope with change. In a room full of potential food, they can literally starve to death. This is not the token of an animal that is winning at life.

Speaking of stupidity and food, one of the likely reasons for their primitive brains is the fact that additionally to being poisonous, eucalyptus leaves (the only thing they eat) have almost no nutritional value. They can't afford the extra energy to think, they sleep more than 80% of their fucking lives. When they are awake all they do is eat, shit and occasionally scream like fucking satan. Because eucalyptus leaves hold such little nutritional value, koalas have to ferment the leaves in their guts for days on end.

Unlike their brains, they have the largest hind gut to body ratio of any mammal. Many herbivorous mammals have adaptations to cope with harsh plant life taking its toll on their teeth, rodents for instance have teeth that never stop growing, some animals only have teeth on their lower jaw, grinding plant matter on bony plates in the tops of their mouths, others have enlarged molars that distribute the wear and break down plant matter more efficiently... Koalas are no exception, when their teeth erode down to nothing, they resolve the situation by starving to death, because they're fucking terrible animals.

Being mammals, koalas raise their joeys on milk (admittedly, one of the lowest milk yields to body ratio... There's a trend here). When the young joey needs to transition from rich, nourishing substances like milk, to eucalyptus (a plant that seems to be making it abundantly clear that it doesn't want to be eaten), it finds it does not have the necessary gut flora to digest the leaves. To remedy this, the young joey begins nuzzling its mother's anus until she leaks a little diarrhoea (actually fecal pap, slightly less digested), which he then proceeds to slurp on. This partially digested plant matter gives him just what he needs to start developing his digestive system. Of course, he may not even have needed to bother nuzzling his mother. She may have been suffering from incontinence. Why? Because koalas are riddled with chlamydia. In some areas the infection rate is 80% or higher. 

This statistic isn't helped by the fact that one of the few other activities koalas will spend their precious energy on is rape. Despite being seasonal breeders, males seem to either not know or care, and will simply overpower a female regardless of whether she is ovulating. If she fights back, he may drag them both out of the tree, which brings us full circle back to the brain‚Ä¶

Koalas have a higher than average quantity of cerebrospinal fluid in their brains. This is to protect their brains from injury... should they fall from a tree. An animal so thick it has its own little built in special ed helmet. I fucking hate them.‚Äù

What I meant is that once you identified your invalidation point you have to keep true to it. It's the only way to learn if the level that you were watching was truthful and worked or not.

Every trade is different, some require tight invalidations because of how close you are to your identified SL, others can be wider and you adjust your size based on that risk.

You also have to accept the fact that you will be wrong.

Most traders on the long run have a win rate averaging around 40% on a multiple year sample. The difference between the good and the bad trader is their ability to cut their losses for shitty trades and let the big ones run, which takes experience.

You can run good for a time being, and I think that one of the great mental difficulties of the job is to accept to take a step back after crushing it for a period of time to avoid giving back everything to the market.

Still holding nearly 150 million dollar in longs on ETHUSD and BTCUSD from the September swing low.

After failing the breakout at 65k USD at the end of August, BTCUSD retreated back to 60k USD where I decided to close my previous long early for a 12 million dollar profit. It became clear to me that we needed another liquidity test and at the same time establish a higher low before going higher. A proper chart analysis showed a high probability of finding that higher low between the 61.8% and the 78.6% Fibonacci levels ($55100-$52424). Fib levels are only reliable if they fit with your liquidation key levels and the previous market structure. Also the way the price approaches the zone in terms of candlesticks, velocity and volume is essential. I layered my buy orders in that zone using a weighting system where both fib levels have an equal level of importance.

I‚Äôve seen many people using indicators without really knowing why they work or why they should work. You need to study them deeply to truly understand them. Only then you will get a better sense of ‚Äòwhy‚Äô and ‚Äòwhen‚Äô. For example for fibs during retracements there is a deeper psychological meaning/theory on why and when these ‚Äòmagical lines‚Äô behave or misbehave.

Without proper long-term time frame analysis, buying fear is basically catching falling knives. And without solid short-term time frame analysis and risk management, you won‚Äôt be able to position yourself and take too many losses. Multiple time frame analysis is paramount.

I am always switching time frames when watching my charts, and I am continuously monitoring new candles that open. Based on your directional bias you need to plot the outcome (body with lower- and upper shadows) of your candles and fit them like a puzzle piece into the previous ones. How far could your shadows go and still reverse in time to create the body that you envisioned? If you do this for every candle, you will be able to blend all those wicks and bodies into one movement. The liquidity pools of certain time frames will become the shadows of the other ones. Once you have mastered this, you will also get clues from these movements. When it gets close but doesn‚Äôt materialize, that‚Äôs a sign of inner strength or exhaustion, depending on the situation. When you do this for years, you familiarized yourself with most of the candle patterns that occur. In some occasions I‚Äôm able to completely rule out a certain price direction (within a certain timeframe) solely based on the closure of the previous candle. It‚Äôs a beautiful game where you‚Äôre just continuously trying to predict every single candle on every single timeframe, while of course going through trial and error.

Loading up on size in extreme volatility is difficult as your margin of error is much higher than during consolidations or regular breakouts. It‚Äôs necessary to scale into that position by using multiple entries that each have their own separate setups. Only by respecting those setups you‚Äôll be able to keep building your position in a way that fits your risk management. If you would just keep buying while the price descends, you can end up in huge losses when your bias turns out to be wrong.

I am staying long for now and looking forward to the price structure in the coming days/weeks.

It's been quite the battle, but I'm finally getting my edge back in the markets. After going back and forth re-adjusting my setups to these new market dynamics, I've slowly managed to recover from my losses and start winning again.

I've had a few good weeks already but it doesn't make sense to me to post anything unless it's pure overall profit. Attached my latest trade, a sharp late entry (BTCUSD) aimed at a nearby liquidity pool.

I'm back to trading my normal size but it has taken me nearly half a year to do so. When you lose your edge, it's important to stay patient and practice proper risk management.

Update: Since I am a very technical trader using high leverage and tight stops to enter my positions,  I need my short time frame structures to be valid and consistent. Ever since the ETFs were introduced, I've had a lot of difficulty seeing my kind of setups in the charts, or have mostly seen them playing out differently.

It's rare to have a new force entering the market and derange your strategies, but eventually you can overcome these changes and adapt. A similar situation happened to me on the 25th of January in 2017. On this day the Chinese exchanges finally introduced trading fees, and the quality and technical consistency in the Chinese charts suddenly disappeared. Ordinary traders and/or investors probably didn't notice a thing, but for me, everything changed.

Patience is key in order to get back in sync with the market. I will continue to test my setups before I start trading my regular position sizes. Whether that is at much higher or lower prices than today is insignificant. Only trade opportunity when your edge is established.

After spotting abundant evidence of weakness in the chart two days ago, I decided to close my longs. Afterwards I was able to open shorts on a few short-term setups yesterday. Today's wick confirmed the weakness, and the below shorts have now been closed as well. I am currently out of position and will practice my patience until a setup appears that matches all my rules.

When everything adds up but the chart tells you different, you listen. Closed my longs yesterday.

Obtained profits:
Bybit: $5.798.105,00
Rollbit: $5.366.501,61

It's not easy to let go of your winners, especially when your analysis for the near future showed a lot more potential. To become biased in one direction is a very dangerous thing and often turns into a death spiral for your portfolio. 

To prevent this, you need to write down your own set of rules. These rules can involve indicators, patterns, candles or anything fundamental. Whenever you are confronted with one of them, you need to set your ego aside and close. Rules are to be ruled by, and yesterday I saw one of mine in the chart.

The final step is acceptance. You need to completely forget about the trade you just closed and look forward with a fresh mindset. It doesn't matter whether the price continues up, down, reverses, rejects,... You followed your rules, and if your rules are good then be confident about them regardless of what the chart shows next.

Taking profits too early can damage your overall performance significantly. Ride your winners, be confident in your targets and move your stops up when the chart allows you to. Still holding my longs.

What a real journey in crypto looks like and why to ignore the eternal green pnl moonboys

2017/2018:

- Eth: x 200    50% profit taken. 50% gone
- Smaller alts: x10 or x20. 10% profit taken 90% gone
- Various other alts: 0% profit taken 100% gone
- Exchange: cryptopia: 100% gone

2019/2020/2021
- Luna: x 69    100% profit taken 0% gone
- Btc: x 12.       60% profit taken 40% gone 
- Other alts: x3, x5, x10.  50% profit taken 50% gone
- Various alts: 0% profit taken 100% gone
- Exchanges/Platforms: Ftx: 80% out, just on time. 20% gone (will get back soon). Anchor: 100% out, just on time. Osmosis (stuck in staking): down 60% before taking it out. 
- Seedrounds: one seedround x 5: profit taken. second seedround: 100% gone. 

2022/2023/2024
- BTC x 3.         No profit taken yet so 0% profit 0% gone
- Sol x   5          No profit taken yet so 0% profit 0% gone
- Various alts: Most were in nice profits and retraced so =0% profit taken & 0% loss
- Nfts: x 3.         No profit taken yet so 0% profit 0% gone. One nft project: 100% gone. 
- Various alts or ordinals: 90 to 100% gone
- Memes: some 100% gone, some x5 or x 10 (partial profit taken, so maybe 50% profit taken until now)
- Two seedrounds: still invested so 0% profit 0% gone

I consider profit when it is in USD or USDT and no longer invested

Lessons in all of this?

1: Diversify and take profit on the way up
2: a real journey in crypto is tough, with many ups and down, many gains and losses, and totally contrary to all the green pnl bullshit moonboys depict on this app.

1: yes, it is a good idea to be disciplined if you are building a stack. Someone felt guilty selling btc to buy something for his wife for example, which is strange because one should never feel guilty about spending some coin on expressing your affection or love for someone you care about deeply. For example, i love buying flowers for my wife every week and am not going to think ¬¥goh...this small amount of btc will be x100 one day so i should not buy her flowers¬¥. 3/ While allocating a big portion of your time is important you also have to find balance to protect your mind. You need mental strength and acuity to avoid being burned out and making wrong critical decisions. Manage physical activity and sleep the best you can.

Just one night with less than 6 hours of sleep negatively impact your cognitive performances greatly.

Physical activity is important to balance your emotions and it helps with handling stress (there will be plenty).

Last cycle I had a biphasic sleep schedule for 3 months (2x 3h naps) to maximize my time in front of the charts during  peak covid degeneracy. 18 hours a day with alarms ringing during my sleep. It paid off extremely well but I paid a big mental price in the process as I still remember it as something quite heavy. I emerged much wealthier but the most out of shape in my life as well. No real social downside due to lockdowns thankfully.

I wouldn't do it again this cycle, but I don't regret doing it.

The lesson here is that if you think you found an opportunity big enough in the market to go hard, do it as nothing even comes close ROI wise.

4/ While the cycles are 'short' the amount of traumatizing events happening is so high that your mind is experiencing constant greed/fear roller coasters, in considerably short timeframes. (See FTX debacle and then Blackrock ETF for example, despair vs hope in months)

Because of that you will always see CT talking about their perception of some stuff that happened 5 months ago that feels like 10 years old. Being aware of that is quite important to refocus yourself into the present and to temper extreme emotions.

Regarding the question, as a directional trader if the market is active 10-15 hours on average, can be more if the market is really volatile.
When the market is slow 1-10 hours.
If the market is really dead, 0-2 hours.

If you have a job I'd say aim for 6 hours during week days, 10h+ on weekends.
No job? 10 hours+ per day

Go hard now, you will have plenty of time to chill in the next bear market.

2/ A financial market is the most brutal form of competitive gaming that exists in the world, consider yourself playing in front of the biggest tryhards on the planet. You think working 60 hours a week is a lot? It's not. You need to be ready to make heavy concessions to allocate enough time to become good at this game, and most importantly to be better than the average. 

You flip burgers at McDonalds? Study during your shift, take trades on the toilets during your break. Get home and study more. Weekends? Forget them and get to work. You'll never make it if you study 3 hours per day 5 days a week. If you have a desk job consider yourself from the most lucky bunch. It's literally the biggest transfer of wealth since decades if not centuries because of its accessibility, it would be a shame to not go all in timewise because you are lazy.

If you're a newb, time is running short but you still have plenty to study and get your shit ready before seeing ballistic price action.

1/ I wanted to throw some ideas about time, its perception in the market and how should you manage your time in here from my pov.

Crypto cycles are 4 years long, it's give or take 3x faster than legacy market cycles. Because the market is extremely young, creativity is high, regulations are low, the tech is new so there is a LOT of stuff happening all of the time. The market and its niches are so wide that it's impossible to stay up to date with everything. 

The fact that everything is happening in such a condensed timeframe is big opportunity wise, but also a burden as it means that you need allocate a lot of time to study, to improve your skills and to stay up to date with wtf is happening.

For those not aware, PnL cards that show just ROI% on margin for the position are useless. I could open a $10 position over and over again till I nail the absolute bottom or top. Then change leverage to 100x after it is well away from entry and post my 1000% PnL card on twitter for clout. Almost everyone on twitter does this, and it is very misleading. That is why you will always see me post the pnl and not ROI%.

I will also add that PnL can also be misleading. I could open a $1m long on one acct and open a $1m short on another acct and whichever one is profitable I share that pnl to twitter. Of course this can be costly due to fees on such large positions, but if it meant 100 people signed up for my paid discord or used my $500 indicator it would be worth it. Hopefully this was an eye opener for anyone that is new to Twitter. Best to be super skeptical of what you see from these influencers.

This person was liquidated at $1300 30 days later.

Bitcoin hit $20k 10 months later.

He was never heard from again.

If you're investing in an asset with a long term target, stick to it, it happens or it doesn't. Be careful adding more variables thinking you can time the market in between. A large majority of us are guilty of this mistake, I included.

In my opinion, the main use case for $ETH, as a layman, is to pay for gas fees.

Network activities on ETH drive gas gwei up.

Higher gas fees create FOMO demand for $ETH tokens because if you don‚Äôt buy it now, you‚Äôll end up buying later at a higher price.

During times of high activity, people were willing to pay insane amounts in gas fees to push their transactions through (e.g., CryptoKitties, DeFi summer, NFT era, etc.).

The problem with this moat is that, with so many L2s built on Ethereum now, they indirectly compete against the mainnet for on-chain activity since they‚Äôre faster and cheaper. Users like us would rather pay cents than hundreds for a transaction.

Not to mention, there are now plenty of alternative L1s that are also cheap and fast.

With gwei at an all-time low for a prolonged period, there really isn‚Äôt any incentive for people to hoard ETH to use for gas fees. Then again, this is also because we haven‚Äôt seen any new killer app being built on Ethereum mainnet that creates fomo.

Thus, the lack of retail demand for this gas token partially explains the weak price action of Ethereum.

From the supply side, the cabal and their friends are continuously selling unannounced, which is kind of sad.

I think the best way to get Ethereum‚Äôs price up is to have the next generation of killer apps (or ponzi schemes) on Ethereum mainnet to drive gas up again‚Äînot on Optimism, Arbitrum, or Base.

Or perhaps some mass adoption that actually uses Ethereum mainnet, which would help drive gas fees up.

Maybe someone has mentioned all this before, and I‚Äôm sure these aren‚Äôt original thoughts.

TL;DR: The price of ETH correlates with gas fees, and L2s cannibalizing its network usage is bad for the price.

My take on Ansem/Cobie etc.

Even though Cobie et al. are right that celebrities entering the space are mostly value extractive grifters, I feel for Ansem that he's a punching bag for people's general discontent at the obvious truth: that almost all the crypto projects are value extractive grifts anyways. 
 Tech, no tech, meme, no meme - behind virtually every token is/was a phony narrative and a pnd (pump and dump).

Ansem, just like all of us, isn't bound to the virtue-signaled rules that everyone opines about but few can walk (like turning down 7 figs to tweet a casino link.  ok, so sue me.)  It seems unfair to hit him on doing a space with iggy - it's an impossible standard.  Yes it gives iggy a platform, yes people will get hurt, but so what.  It's an inefficiency that people will exploit, until there aren't enough desperate suckers zipping their life savings into this shit.  Because it's all pnds.

However, I agree with the general consensus that Ansem has lost touch with the reality that these are mostly all scams (or he's being willfully ignorant to his benefit).  He deserves a bit of pushback for that. 
 Getting 100x'es is a thing of the past, except maybe for the sharpest minds, or the people running the casino.  No not every project is some huge gamechanger that will transform society, sometimes its just a fucking pnd.  I mean how many pnd's do we have to go through until you figure out, it's all pnds.  Listen up.  It's all pnds.  Pencils down, kid.  The answer?  It's all pnds.

But at the same time, I mean what the hell else is Ansem going to tweet about wrt crypto.  And whatever he is tweeting, well... "it's good for the game", to use the poker saying.  In this case, the "game" being to find another desperate sucker to buy the coin, nft, option, perp, governance token, presale, ico, points, or whatever else bullshit you dump on them.  It's almost an art to convince someone a weekend hackathon project is somehow $1bn on paper.  It's all pnds.

This is really no judgment against Ansem though.  Being the main "talking head" in the space almost necessitates a Jim Cramer-esque demeanor of excitement towards all these coins.  Otherwise what else are you going to do, be a monk?  It's all pnds.

And I'm not saying I'm any better, by the way.  We are living in a world of sin, and when players enter the squid game looking for riches, few will win, many will die.  So let's not pretend they can all make it by all doing the same shit - almost all of the shit here is a zero or negative sum game.  You only win when others lose.  In the case of memecoins, they are already highly cabal-controlled and will be "full stack hitlered" at increasingly faster speeds going forward as the meta evolves towards equilibrium.  Because yep, you guessed it: it's all pnds.

By now you already know the narrative: memecoin supercycle.

How did we get here?  Let's walk back a bit.  Why do people invest so much in companies that don't pay any dividends?  You might say "share buybacks", but that is basically saying "someone else will buy it".  What seems so solid - real companies and profits - in some cases become more about memes and narratives than people want to admit.

Today you can find stocks that probably trade well above any nuts and bolts value. In memecoin terms, TSLA is almost like an "Elon Coin", and that's why it trades so high.  As long as people want to buy, it can remain this way.

To make clear the silliness, imagine you own a bunch of real estate that has some valuation, but when packaged together, the package somehow trades at many multiples of that value.  It's hard for normies to wrap their head around, but this "meme premium" is from speculators creating their own zero sum game around that asset, hoping to sell it to another speculator.

What is happening?  Gambling revenues are booming, as people are either getting increasingly desperate or rich.  Whether the move is TSLA calls or shitcoin perps, these are essentially additional outlets for gambling.  In this case, many on CT are gambling addicts, hoping to catch a 100x by buying into (insert cashgrab solana shitter here).

Ponzis have been part of crypto (for better or worse) for a decade, including the ICO era, NFTs, play to earn, and so on.  Almost all projects were cash grabs that started with a flimsy premise, created a ponzi/token around it, and sold out like hotcakes.  Left curve buyers bought into the premise and right curve buyers bought in because they were first, and the price went up.

The arrival of these memecoins, especially the ones with no utility, are the purest expression of the ponzi, as the ponzi is right in your face, the only thing it promises. It's also more efficient than dealing with NFTs or other complicated systems.

Another aspect is that liquidity can hide the ball. Shitcoins (and nfts) use low liquidity to meme that your bag is more valuable than it is. If for example a tiny bit of some shitcoin trades at some high price, that doesn't mean the sum of everyone's bag is worth that much, yet most are inclined to believe it. This is a kind of arbitrage on perception vs reality that these assets exploit basically.

Anyways, back to today.  In everybody's dream outcome, BTC marches to infinity ($100k+), we magically get a lot more retail investors who want to buy your meme coins, and your girlfriend has a girlfriend.  And if ETF flows continue (or accelerate), then yeah, that's where we are going.  So I recommend staying on the train.

But I think there is a middle ground option, and I'm getting prepared for that possibility, where ETF flows taper off.  Every indicator is flashing now.  OG retail is definitely here, and they are spraying.  Influenzas are all shilling cashgrab shitters daily.  Funding is 100%apy to long, sometimes much higher on alts.  Fast money from BTC appreciation went everywhere, but some places are more leaky than others and people will have to take an L at some point.  Also, ETH is still an expensive chain to use for most applications.

A ponzi system needs more and more oxygen to breathe, and unless it gets that oxygen from somewhere, it can quickly deflate.

To buy memecoins now, you have to think who the last buyers will be.  In regards to small cap memes, most of retail will get sucked in by manipulated charts/PA and astroturfed discussions, and their money will get funneled into professional shitcoin producers.  Today, Twitter is a battlefield of which KOL can shill which cashgrab shitter memecoin, those posts get boosted by these pirates and you will get slaughtered on chain.  Yes, someone extremely determined can win.  But if you choose to play on chain as a low info normie, just know that there will be few winners and many losers.

To leverage long now, you have to pay obscene funding and fees.  It's a completely different bet than spot for this reason.  There is a difference between what is likely to happen and what is a bad bet, eg. celtics probably win, but laying 10-1 is a bad bet.   And with this much juice, this is where it starts to get into bad bet territory.

Also, a lot of gamblers are getting pushed towards more and more leverage which amplifies the possibility of a death wick - that April 2021 kind of wick where I lost $100m in a day.  There, bitcoin went from 68k to 40k.  Study the run up in 2020-2021, when bigger wicks were increasing in occurrence.  Study 2019.  Hell, study every year in the book.

Today, I think you should stay on the train.  Be 100% in spot crypto, mostly majors, and play somewhat defensively, knowing we are in later innings.  Don't lose your shirt.  These indicators (extremely high funding, extremely bullish sentiment, mania, etc.) can get more extreme, but they always reset in the end.  For every gigalong getting liquidated, there is another guy buying that liquidation. Be that guy.  This is now a game of survival.  Most will not survive.  All you have to do to win, is survive.

For me, my home run is to grab a giant red wick or two on the path to infinity, and make money both ways.  But whichever way the ball goes, I will be a winner.  I have never forgotten the value of a dollar, and I never will.  Champions adjust.  I'll see you at the citadel.

So, with the "etf headline", the market tipped its hand.  The level 0 play was to market bang on the etf announcement.  Many people knowing this, moved to level 1, longing in advance, frontrunning the announcement and trying to get sells off on the news.  When Tree changed (even as a meme) from having two buttons to having one button, this was a sign to me that level 1 might be the more popular paradigm, also as levels were quite high.

This led to a predicted pump on the news,  followed by a sell wicking to deep lows and ending lower than where we started, as there were prior longs that needed to be unwound.  Congratulations if you played out a trading plan along these lines.

I think, while the bitcoin etfs are ultimately structurally very bullish, over the next few days is bearish as many longs are over extended, and so on short timeframes, I wouldn't even mind seeing lows a fair bit lower from where we are now, and mostly I aim for tactical shorts.  Most in the game are tourists and are not faithful of the ultimate vision that BTC goes to ATH.  In that scenario that we get nice entries for BTC, I will load up very big.

In regards to ETH/BTC longs, whenever considering a spread trade, I only take the trade if I like both legs of the trade.  Failure to do this cost me millions of dollars last cycle, as I repeatedly put on "widowmaker" trades, shorting the juicy side at my peril.  In this case, the BTCUSD short leg is juicy as BTC is primed to double over the next year, so I see no reason to enter this trade (over a longer timeframe).

However, on a shorter timeframe, I expect the market will rinse a bit, and the market has tipped its hand about ETH rotations by pumping ETH on the headline today, I think ETH/BTC is probably good for a bit, even though I am ultimately a BTC+SOL believer, I like the rotations.  But I think ultimately we get some pullback, so my main play on short timeframes is to just ride down to an expected pullback before firing back in big.  It still weighs in the back of my mind that the last 2 ETF launches have been stone tops, and so at least in the short term that is what I expect.

Now what to do about the "etf headline" tomorrow, given that everyone has already exhausted themselves playing it?  I think it will mostly be a nothing burger.  In general for iterated games I like to go one level higher when its run back, so in this case I think trying to sell earlier is better.

Finally, 1000BONK, the poster child for alts, bounced hard off 0.01.  We have hit halftime for this cycle overall.  It is interesting to watch these altcoins, as if a real bull emerges with BTC at ATH, the wealth effect can spray onto alts that will get a second wind and go into mania.  For me there is no play yet but something to keep in mind that if you are sure BTC will 2x, there will be 10+ x'es in the rough.

When a parabolic regime begins on high timeframe, the strategy of being long from the ignition move and then holding until wide trailing stops are hit is best.  This is called "long until wrong."  I think it is unwise to give up core positions this early.

I don't pretend to know where the top is.  But in December of 2020, traders lost their mind shorting Bitcoin at 10k, 12k, 16k, 20k, 24k, 30k as the number kept going up to a mindboggling 69k, well over many people's belief.  People either lost their shirt shorting or locked in only tiny gains as the price moved many multiples higher.  This is why I am open to astronomical numbers: 200k btc, 100b bonk, or whatever.  I'm not saying this is likely.  I just don't pretend to know where we go.  I let the market show me.

In Dec 2020, I was already making eight figures.  But in the next 3 months that followed, I would make 9 figures, as I gassed it where most would exit, and didn't enter my own bias about what the price should be, but rather just allowed the market to do its thing.

The time when it flushed to 55k during the first deep correction (similar to "Jesse Livermore's Speculative Chart"), would have then been the trigger to sell.  A trailing stop strategy is guaranteed to give back a lot of gains, but you'll have captured the majority of the total move trading in this way, which will outperform.  Of course, I succumbed to the pressure and ignored my own advice.

On the short term, I think we have had a blowoff into memes, it feels like a mini-cycle a bit, and it was reasonable to tp a bit to buy lower.  From here, it seems there are too many participants eager to buy dips for there to be sustained drawdowns, so I would generally favor the long side.  As for bonk, I have no clue but I honestly think the bonk ape makes it, and surprises everyone.

If you're still on the sidelines, good luck.

Thoughts about the FTX liquidation engine:

On April 2021, my account had 8 figures after being liquidated on 9 figures of position.  This liquidation was assumed by Alameda because apparently the entire liquidation procedure was fake.  Instead of liquidating participants on book, they took over liquidating accounts manually.

This didn't make sense to me because the point of taking over accounts would presumably be to liquidate the user on the frontend, but keep their assets and profit from the difference on the backend.  In this case though, I kept the money, so the issue to me seemed more benign than adversarial.

Signs were there, such as FTX not having an on-chain cold wallet, and the insurance fund number wouldn't hold up under scrutiny.  It pains me that no one checked these simple facts.  I wanted to say something at the time, but many around me told me it would be better if I stayed quiet.

During the LUNA collapse, FTX/Alameda assumed the liquidated positions which would typically mean revert.  In this case, the "black swan" happened and the asset went to zero, against the predictions of a gaussian model.  They got wiped out.
TLDR: Justin Sun allegedly yield farming with Huobi deposits.

Don't understand the Eigenlayer and re-staking narrative?

That is purposefully done by gatekeeping pseudo-intellectual larps who overcomplicate things in an effort to make their protocol look smart.

I will explain it as simple as possible here, and why the potential is massive:

Think of Eigenlayer as an extra layer to use your already staked ETH for more yield. Staking ETH typically meant locking it up to support the Ethereum network, earning rewards in return.

Eigenlayer adds a twist: it lets you use that same staked ETH to support other projects or services and earn extra yield on top of what you are already earning.

That activity to earn extra yield through Eigenlayer is called re-staking.

Similar to how Lido makes your staked ETH liquid and lets you use it for other purposes to earn extra yield like borrowing/lending:

Re-staking also gives you liquid staked ETH that earns yield on top of Eigenlayer activities passively. The yield is expected to be around 15%.

15% YIELD ON ETH! That's insane!

Here comes the problem though:

For each layer that ETH is being used to earn yield, it adds an extra layer of risk.

Even the layer of ETH -> stETH has 2 layers of risk to it (smart contracts breaking) from the actual ETH staking contract and the Lido smart contract.

Now imagine that there will be several more layers, each layer increasing the risk premium of your underlying ETH on top of stETH.

Each layer has a claim to your native ETH on mainnet, until one part of the chain isn't fully backed somehow and it potentially breaks.

Keeping this into consideration, a 15% yield does seem fairly priced by the market for this risk premium.

Why is this such a massive opportunity?

The market for idle assets on Ethereum is enormous. TVL of Lido and Aave make up the majority of crypto. If you consider Curve and Uniswap stable pairs, it gets even larger.

In fact, the trading/speculating side of crypto that you see on Twitter (such as memecoins) is only less than 10% of the overall market.

This will likely be a catalyst that fuels up Ethereum's ecosystem like never seen before.

Ethereum vs Solana - A Tale of Two Ecosystems.

The design of Ethereum is a well-thought-out cityscape, where each layer serves a distinct purpose for settlements.

Layer-3+: The corner shops where small trades like buying a coffee happen quickly with ease. 

You don't need to perfectly verify the transactions for such small amounts; also applies to crypto gaming.

This is already live as Arbitrum Orbit allows for people to build Layer-3 dApp chains. Gas fees are already comparable to Solana on Arbitrum Nova.

Layer-2: The business district where bigger transactions like buying a car or buying a property is securely done.

It requires a bit more verification since these are larger purchases.

Layer-1: The fortified bank.

Really big settlements in the millions and more will happen here (such as keeping a savings account).

This also already happens. People with large sums of funds on-chain tend to keep it securely on mainnet Ethereum (Aave/Lido) instead of Layer-2s.
-

When you go down each layer, the decentralisation gets sacrificed for faster speed and lower fees.

A simple act like buying a cup of coffee doesn't require a written contract or a lawyer (although it could!).

But if you are buying a house, you would want the deal to go a bit slower to make sure everything is securely happening. Paying higher fees also makes up for that security.

Solana on the other hand has a single-chain approach,  presenting a different approach by focusing on high throughput and low fees at the cost of centralisation.

Its higher hardware and bandwidth requirements for nodes have led to a centralisation of nodes among few providers.

In a way, Solana already is comparable to a Layer-3+ on Ethereum.

Sacrificing decentralisation is the reason why million-dollar settlements will not take place on Solana and why the majority of crypto's TVL is secured on Ethereum's mainnet.

It is useful to note that Ethereum holds 50x the size of Solana's TVL, while only 12x higher in token valuation.

This difference between TVL and token valuation is important to consider, as Solana's price has increased by 2x in the past month but its TVL has only increased by 30%.

This further reinforces the idea that Solana is a settlement layer for fast, cheap transactions.

But keeping your money securely on Solana for the long-term? Not a smart idea.

A common myth is that once interest rates get cut, markets will rally.

In fact, the opposite will happen.

Historically, rate cuts have preceded financial downturns such as the dot-com bubble of 2000 and the Global Financial Crash of 2008.

These bubbles were popped AFTER interest rates had been cut.

We find ourselves in a similar situation in 2023; this time it is even more obvious as to why it will happen.

Bonds have been in a devastating bear market like never before. They have lost around 60% of their value since 2020.

The implications of this are:

- People are dumping treasury bills into the open market

- People aren't buying up those treasury bills, or having new ones issued to them

- The US Treasury struggles to pay their liabilities with high interest rates.

The US Treasury is facing a fiscal challenge as a result of this. 

They desperately need to revive the bond market and get more people to lend them money.

Solution to this problem is simple:

Even a hint or a singular rate cut from the Federal Reserve could send investors flocking back to bonds, aligning with the US Treasury's needs.

People will start piling into bonds again as they expect interest rates to continue declining, and therefore, start a bull market for bonds. The US Treasury is saved.

When this happens, risk assets get neglected as the herd moves into bonds with hopeful upwards momentum.

Thus.. a bear market starts.

The Fed funds futures market currently priced in the first upcoming rate cut of 0.25% at: June 12, 2024.

Keep in mind that this futures market gives extremely rough predictions and it can fluctuate wildly on a daily basis.

In my opinion, we have smooth sailing of a bull market until the first rate cut. Markets will continue to rally.

From the crash of 2022 to the rally of 2023, asset prices have rebound to near all-time-highs.

While traditional markets have bounced back, crypto has failed to recover.

Why has crypto not recovered like other assets?

In an earlier thread I wrote about how the Federal Reserve once controlled money supply growth, and this has power shift is now in the hands of the US Treasury.

Now, US Treasury holders, with $1 trillion+ in interest payments, are the key players propping up the global economy.

These interest payments far exceed the amount of Quantitative Tightening done by the Federal Reserve.

As a result, money supply has returned to inflationary.

So, Quantitative Easing is going directly to Treasury holders this time.

Who are these Treasury holders?

Typically, they fall into the upper-middle-class category or institutional investors.

Unlike those struggling to make ends meet, these Treasury holders do not spend their interest earnings on necessities like food, electricity, cars, or holidays.

Instead, they invest this money into financial assets like equities and real estate.

A different kind of spending, one that does not inflate the Consumer Price Index (CPI) but keeps asset prices strong.

So while we have CPI at 3.2% currently, it does not tell the whole story about inflation.

This change in spending patterns explains the drop in CPI inflation with Treasury holders investing in assets rather than spending on consumables.

Remember the Covid stimulus checks?

3 rounds of stimulus checks were sent to people of low-income.

These people spent their unexpected money on necessities (food, electricity, other bills) and some luxuries, like cars, causing CPI inflation in those areas.

Compare that to the interest payments to Treasury holders.

US Treasury interest payments = stimulus checks for the wealthy.

Instead of buying groceries, they are investing in stocks and properties.

Why has this asset price inflation not trickled down to crypto?

Interestingly, these upper-middle-class bond holders have no interest in crypto.

The demographic is just different, generally boomers who are content with the traditional financial system.

Unlike the bottom 50% of the population who gambled their stimulus checks on platforms like Robinhood or on crypto memecoins, bond holders stick to more conventional investments.

Unless stablecoin market caps start increasing, it is clear that there are no money inflows into crypto yet.

As currencies such as JPY/TRY/ARS inflate, the borrowed debt will gradually become worthless.

Inflating currencies follow a one-way road to hyperinflation. They never deflate. We are using this to our advantage.

As the price of Bitcoin rises and/or the currencies depreciate, your access to margin increases. You can repeat this process to buy even more Bitcoin.

A decline in the value of Bitcoin would reduce returns.

It is a system that demands more participants taking on more debt, every year, forever, just to prevent collapse.

The solution? Immigration.

It is far more practical to accept a 30-year-old immigrant ready to work and take on debt than to wait 18 years for a newborn to enter the workforce.

Japan's economy tells a cautionary tale. Their low population growth and strict immigration policies have prioritised social cohesion over economic growth. 

But this approach has backfired. Their economy is down the drain, and the terrible economic environment already has caused social unrest.

People view Japan as a utopia, but this could not be further from the truth. 

Mental health issues are rampant, poverty is soaring, and the currency is inflating rapidly. Most of the population are overworked zombies and this is all an indirect result of their tough immigration policies.

In comparison, Europe, the USA and GCC countries are accepting immigrants, fueling their economies, and, in a sense, doing it right.

Anti-immigration policies lead to a stagnant economy. 

While concerns about social unrest caused by immigration exist, the long-term economic damage by a declining birth rate creates greater and more lasting social problems.

Education of children
(long post)

So many people ask me about the education of their children, home/public/private schooling, what is best place or best country etc?

Forget about all that. Go back to the basics. 
The most important thing in my humble opinion one can give a child, is 
1: a proper example
2: love and understanding
3: patience
4: nature
5: letting go when the time is right
6: reduce toxin exposure

To go deeper into each point:

1: your children copy and reflect a lot of what you do, so if you are kind, patient, loving, understanding, and radiate good energy, they will pick up on this and copy this. shout, yell, be angry and impatient, and that is what you will get back and create

2: love and understanding means appreciating the ¬¥pureness¬¥ children still have. they don¬¥t function all the time from the rational mind, live in the moment, and can really ¬¥be¬¥ often. appreciate that and understand you can also learn from that. They are also a mirror/reflection for you. People always want to educate their kids so much, learn them things all the time, force education onto them, while forgetting children are often just great to be around, play with, and a great mirror for your own inadequacies. 

3: breath, walk, allow. breath, walk, allow. breath, walk allow. they will always test your patience, but never yell at them, and stop saying ¬¥no¬¥ all the time. don¬¥t need to mention of course to never hit your child. 

4: healthy food, healthy exercise, healthy environment, if you can do as much in nature as possible. we are animals after all and nature and being outside naturally calms children down. limit electronic devices as much as possible. 

5: don¬¥t be clingy, let them explore to the max. put boundaries of course, but allow and let go when the time is right. each person has their own path, so don¬¥t force your opinions and judgments and goals onto them

6: children/baby bed at least 1m away from every power socket. no wifi radiation close. no babymonitor next to head baby. minimal amounts of processed foods and all kind of toxic crab, healthy water from glass water bottles or filtered. just a general rule: the closer it is to the real thing from nature the better

Just as a personal example. I was born in a rich country, good schools, all opportunities, but i was emotionally messed up also partly because my parents were a bad example due to the fact they were emotionally underdeveloped and their relationship was toxic. My wife was born in a very poor country with few opportunities, but with a very loving mother and family life, and she turned out a lot better when she was young than i did. So stop worrying about sending your child to the best swiss private boarding school and instead focus on working on yourself which will reflect in a better atmosphere in your home hence healthier/happier/better educated children.

One hears it all the time: ¬¥market manipulation going on¬¥, ¬¥whales are f**cking us over¬¥, the ¬¥cabal¬¥ is pumping that coin

Have received a fair amount of whales/large crypto currency holders on my forest garden mountain, and i have asked many, and none confirm there is some kind of organised cabal. In my humble opinion:
- what does ¬¥cabal¬¥ even mean, has anyone even defined it? does that mean a group of crypto-whales working together? or are you just going along with conspiracy shit on x? 
- yes, some whales do work together on exchanges, but pushing a 15 billion volume asset around is basically impossible with so many exchanges. You would need serious size, and that would draw attention. 
- yes, some whales do work together to pump & dump alts, but there is no ¬¥organised cabal¬¥ doing this as far as i know
- yes, large cryptocurrency holders take enormous positions in certain coins, memes for example, start pushing a narrative on x, and then unload, but that is common knowledge. I would not say there is some ¬¥cabal¬¥ behind it.

Study reversals after huge dumps

If you are interested in short term trading, can¬¥t emphasize enough to study how this market reverses after huge dumps (like 5th of august and last night/today)

- the extreme sell-off candles on the 1m and 5m charts, meaning strong liquidations happening
- the bounce that follows and within a couple of hours price is almost back to the lows, but no newer low is made, and an hourly bull div shows up
- the 4h engulfing candle
- subsequent resistance at important (e)ma¬¥s before stabilising and moving higher
- keep an eye on volume too
- the shifts in sentiment on crypto(twitter) as well, the move from mass fud & fear to ¬¥oh..it is all ok¬¥, to ¬¥woaw, nothing happened actually¬¥

Get so many questions on how i trade/invest, why, how i allocate etc, so let me answer this all in one tweet. Also yesterday all these questions why i enter a trade etc. 

Ok, so

1: long term spot btc holdings in multi-sig wallets. This is my savingsaccount during the bullmarket. I hold my money in btc during a bullmarket, and in usd & usdt during a bearmarket

2: btc on and exchange to use as collateral to trade perps short term

3: usdt on another exchange to trade perps short term

4: alts and nft allocations, stored when possible in cold storage of course 

5: some money on banks, apps like n-26, revolut, vivid, etc, for daily spending, but all very little, prefer holding btc in the bull.

Suicide

¬¥Tim, dude, is this morbid stuff really necessary?¬¥. 
Yes it is, and i am not avoiding the tough topics on this account. 

Suicide is a topic nobody wants to talk about in life, or in the cryptospace, but it happens more often than most realise. 

I don¬¥t receive the heavy cases personally who are on the verge of suicide, i recommend them to go a clinic first and seek professional help, but just through talking on dm¬¥s i have prevented various crypto-people from ending their lives in desperation (especially on the super red liquidation days in crypto). 

Most people who are temporarily desperate just need some perspective, some nice words, take it easy, learn some meditation, and realise there is more in life than money, and that having a normal job for a while to save up again to re-invest in crypto is fine. 

The heavier cases, people who really consider it, and a point i came to myself when i was 22 for just one day, i recommend to seek serious psychological help or seek out real healers. My book also has the story what happened to me (can download free on articles section on my website). 
90% of the solution is admitting one has a problem, and no shame in admitting one thought of ending one¬¥s life, it is the one right we all have in a way. Most people don¬¥t want to do it, and are just desperate and in need of some help. In case you see or hear someone around you in this state, or online, be kind, reach out, and tell them to look for professional help. In case you are not that desperate and need some tips, my dm is always open. 

Life is beautiful, i know it is not easy sometimes, but as the buddha said, we came in this world to suffer and learn, so realise that the suffering is the best teacher in the world if you take it serious and use it to turn inside.

Style/Cost of living 
long tweet

Since so many asked and are curious about style of living/cost of living/moving to a more remote place, 
let me describe a bit more about it

I am not a sour armpit smelling hippy, nor do we live some extravagant or dogmatic life. I like everything about existence: from technology to simple-living, love it all, and we are not ¬¥against anything¬¥, on the contrary. We just like to live close to nature because it provides us with quality air, quality food, and quality outdoor activities, so we visit cities when we make trips. 

There are many remote areas in Europe, and with starlink one can live in any place well and work online. This area was very cheap 12 year ago, and is now getting more popular, but if one goes remote one can still find large properties that need fixing up for 300k for example, or smaller ones for 200k. Key to finding these properties is to go a bit more remote of course. The key is of course to be resilient internally, willing to be creative yourself and build up the land with permaculture/forest garden techniques etc. When i moved in this place here it was a shithole literally, now it is paradise, but it took slow dedication for 10 years+. Can¬¥t emphasize that enough: if you want to build a garden, start young, it takes time. 

Cost of living is:
- water: 10 euro a month
- electricity: 0: solar panels
- mortgage: 0: house paid off
- fuel: 0: electric car, charged with solar panels
- heating: 0: wood in winter and hot water with heat pump that goes with solar panels
- food: 1000 a month: have most vegetable, eggs, fruits, nuts, etc from the property, we go to restaurants as well
- car insurance: 30 a month
- house insurance: 30 a month
- health insurance family of 5: 500 a month. This is a great private insurance that covers 100% in the country we live and allows one to go to any hospital in world and it covers 90%. Very cheap for what it offers
- phone: 50 a month
- starlink: 50 a month
- tax house: 40 a month
- fuel tractor/garden equipment: 20 a month
- garbage collection: 5 euro a month
- extra: 500 a month: diapers, chicken minerals, duckfood, car check-up, netflix, spotify, all that kind of extra¬¥s

So 2235 euro a month, for family of 5. So 26k a year. 
Many years i lived alone and i spend less than 1000 a month, which allowed me to save and eventually invest in crypto. 

Of course there are other one-off expenses too, buying plants etc, trips etc, but these are the fixed costs more or less, and we can cut that down more if needed and are less of course if you are alone or have a smaller family. 

Just saying that it is totally possible to live a comfy, simpler life, without sacrificing modern comforts etc. 
As usual the key is inner development. Once you are calm on the inside, the rest will come naturally and your life-style and home will be a reflection of your inner state of being

Get a lot of dm¬¥s from people asking how to start with (forest) gardening, how to set up an eco-project, things like that.

Invincibility vs keeping financial reserves for health emergencies

Unfortunately, many family members in the poor latin country where my wife is from, have fallen ill the last couple of years with various things: cancer, covid, viruses, bacterial infections. Due to the bad state of public hospitals, any visit to one of these places is fraught with risks because of bad hygienic circumstances and anti-biotic resistant superbugs. 

Luckily, thanks to cashing out enough in the 2017 and 2021 bullmarkets, i had (in $ during bearmarkets) and have (in btc during bullmarkets) enough financial reserves to send them to the best private clinics in their country or abroad. Literally various lives were saved because of being able to do this, and the joy to have them still with us is of course enormous.

I know many young crypto traders/investors on here feel invincible, but i strongly recommend that if you can, you always keep some reserves for health emergencies for yourself, your family-members, or friends. Nothing feels better than spending it on them instead of on a supercar. Nobody is invincible, and illness and death come knocking on the door of us all one day. No need to live in fear of course, but being aware and prepared is always useful.
